[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":1358},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fmemory-leak-explained-and-common-causes\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fmemory-leak-explained-and-common-causes\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fmemory-leak-explained-and-common-causes\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fmemory-leak-explained-and-common-causes\u002F":1334,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fmisc\u002F2023\u002F11\u002F06\u002Fmemory-leak-explained-and-common-causes\u002F":1343},"\u002Fother\u002F20231106\u002F3142223114\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":1316,"date":1317,"description":1318,"extension":1319,"lang":1320,"meta":1321,"navigation":238,"path":1322,"readingMinutes":1323,"seo":1324,"standalone":1325,"stem":1326,"tags":1327,"tldr":1331,"updated":1317,"url":1332,"__hash__":1333},"content\u002Fen\u002FMisc\u002Fmemory-leak-explained-and-common-causes.md","Why You Should Understand Memory Leaks (memory leak)","9152683074",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":1306},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,34,37,43,53,56,84,91,98,105,109,112,115,121,128,131,249,268,295,319,322,327,330,426,432,545,552,566,570,573,606,616,622,626,633,636,1093,1096,1282,1289,1293,1296,1299,1302],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"\"Memory\" is one of those words that matters to every developer — because how memory gets used directly affects how your program runs. So this post is about memory leaks.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"a-bit-about-memory","A bit about memory",[17,25,26],{},"Think of memory like an hourglass.",[17,28,29],{},[30,31],"img",{"alt":32,"src":33},"Hourglass","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fother\u002Fmemory_leak\u002Fisray_notarray_hourglass_broken_--stylize_750_--v_5.2_a0e3b05e-87a9-416d-88f6-58a60c8479f9.png",[17,35,36],{},"You have a finite amount of memory, and when you're done using a chunk you have to return (release) it. Otherwise you run out.",[17,38,39],{},[30,40],{"alt":41,"src":42},"Out of memory","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fother\u002Fmemory_leak\u002F2023-11-06%2019.57.51.png",[44,45,46],"blockquote",{},[17,47,48,52],{},[49,50,51],"strong",{},"Note","\nWindows pops up a \"Your computer is low on memory\" warning when RAM is running out.",[17,54,55],{},"There are a few different kinds of memory:",[57,58,59,66,72,78],"ul",{},[60,61,62,65],"li",{},[49,63,64],{},"Main memory"," — RAM (Random Access Memory). The memory we usually mean — where the data your program needs at runtime lives.",[60,67,68,71],{},[49,69,70],{},"Cache memory"," — Stores data the CPU needs frequently. Acts as a fast intermediate so the CPU doesn't keep hitting RAM.",[60,73,74,77],{},[49,75,76],{},"Virtual memory"," — Simulates more RAM by using your disk. When RAM fills up, less-used data spills onto disk to free RAM.",[60,79,80,83],{},[49,81,82],{},"Read-only memory (ROM)"," — For data that doesn't change, like BIOS.",[17,85,86,87,90],{},"What about SSD and HDD? Those are ",[49,88,89],{},"storage devices",", not memory — different category, won't dig into them here.",[17,92,93,94,97],{},"The one we care about for memory leaks is ",[49,95,96],{},"main memory"," (RAM) — because when a program leaks, it's RAM that's running out.",[44,99,100],{},[17,101,102,104],{},[49,103,51],{},"\nThese days I'd say 8GB RAM is the floor, 16GB is the standard, and 32GB is a reasonable target if you're a developer. For document-only use 8GB is fine. For heavier workloads — image processing, games — go 16GB or more.",[12,106,108],{"id":107},"whats-a-memory-leak","What's a memory leak?",[17,110,111],{},"Now that we've got the basics, let's get to memory leaks.",[17,113,114],{},"The concept is simple. Like the hourglass — memory gets used as the program runs (sand flows down), and when it's done the hourglass flips and the memory comes back.",[17,116,117],{},[30,118],{"alt":119,"src":120},"Returning memory","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002Fblog\u002Fother\u002Fmemory_leak\u002Ff2c6f7b752e64ba8aeae56490a4c4ec5.gif",[17,122,123,124,127],{},"That return process is called ",[49,125,126],{},"Garbage Collection"," (GC) — the runtime reclaims memory that's no longer in use.",[17,129,130],{},"GC is an automated memory management system. When some memory isn't being referenced anymore, GC frees it. In code:",[132,133,138],"pre",{"className":134,"code":135,"language":136,"meta":137,"style":137},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function foo() {\n  const a = 1;\n  const b = 2;\n  const c = 3;\n  return a + b + c;\n}\n\nfoo();\n","js","",[139,140,141,158,177,192,207,227,233,240],"code",{"__ignoreMap":137},[142,143,146,150,154],"span",{"class":144,"line":145},"line",1,[142,147,149],{"class":148},"sWyjQ","function",[142,151,153],{"class":152},"sj_SG"," foo",[142,155,157],{"class":156},"sMAXC","() {\n",[142,159,161,164,168,171,174],{"class":144,"line":160},2,[142,162,163],{"class":148},"  const",[142,165,167],{"class":166},"sCcAr"," a",[142,169,170],{"class":148}," =",[142,172,173],{"class":166}," 1",[142,175,176],{"class":156},";\n",[142,178,180,182,185,187,190],{"class":144,"line":179},3,[142,181,163],{"class":148},[142,183,184],{"class":166}," b",[142,186,170],{"class":148},[142,188,189],{"class":166}," 2",[142,191,176],{"class":156},[142,193,195,197,200,202,205],{"class":144,"line":194},4,[142,196,163],{"class":148},[142,198,199],{"class":166}," c",[142,201,170],{"class":148},[142,203,204],{"class":166}," 3",[142,206,176],{"class":156},[142,208,210,213,216,219,222,224],{"class":144,"line":209},5,[142,211,212],{"class":148},"  return",[142,214,215],{"class":156}," a ",[142,217,218],{"class":148},"+",[142,220,221],{"class":156}," b ",[142,223,218],{"class":148},[142,225,226],{"class":156}," c;\n",[142,228,230],{"class":144,"line":229},6,[142,231,232],{"class":156},"}\n",[142,234,236],{"class":144,"line":235},7,[142,237,239],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":238},true,"\n",[142,241,243,246],{"class":144,"line":242},8,[142,244,245],{"class":152},"foo",[142,247,248],{"class":156},"();\n",[17,250,251,252,255,256,259,260,263,264,267],{},"After ",[139,253,254],{},"foo()"," returns, GC sees that ",[139,257,258],{},"a",", ",[139,261,262],{},"b",", and ",[139,265,266],{},"c"," aren't referenced anymore, and reclaims the memory they used.",[17,269,270,271,274,275,277,278,281,282,259,285,287,288,291,292,294],{},"Variable assignment in JS works via reference. When you write ",[139,272,273],{},"const a = 1",", you're pointing the name ",[139,276,258],{}," at the memory holding ",[139,279,280],{},"1",". If you then write ",[139,283,284],{},"a = 2",[139,286,258],{}," now points at ",[139,289,290],{},"2",", and since nothing references ",[139,293,280],{}," anymore, GC reclaims it.",[44,296,297],{},[17,298,299,301,302,305,306,309,310,312,313,315,316,318],{},[49,300,51],{},"\nAnother way to release memory is to point the variable at ",[139,303,304],{},"null"," (e.g., ",[139,307,308],{},"a = null","). GC then reclaims the original ",[139,311,280],{},". Does ",[139,314,304],{}," itself take memory? Not really — ",[139,317,304],{}," is a JavaScript runtime value, every \"null\" points at the same singleton, so it doesn't bloat memory.",[17,320,321],{},"That's the happy path. Now the unhappy paths — common ways memory actually leaks.",[323,324,326],"h3",{"id":325},"event-listeners","Event listeners",[17,328,329],{},"Classic example — attaching a listener to an element:",[132,331,333],{"className":134,"code":332,"language":136,"meta":137,"style":137},"function addLister() {\n  const el = document.getElementById('el');\n  el.addEventListener('click', () => {\n    console.log('clicked');\n  });\n}\n\naddLister();\n",[139,334,335,344,369,391,406,411,415,419],{"__ignoreMap":137},[142,336,337,339,342],{"class":144,"line":145},[142,338,149],{"class":148},[142,340,341],{"class":152}," addLister",[142,343,157],{"class":156},[142,345,346,348,351,353,356,359,362,366],{"class":144,"line":160},[142,347,163],{"class":148},[142,349,350],{"class":166}," el",[142,352,170],{"class":148},[142,354,355],{"class":156}," document.",[142,357,358],{"class":152},"getElementById",[142,360,361],{"class":156},"(",[142,363,365],{"class":364},"sTRMh","'el'",[142,367,368],{"class":156},");\n",[142,370,371,374,377,379,382,385,388],{"class":144,"line":179},[142,372,373],{"class":156},"  el.",[142,375,376],{"class":152},"addEventListener",[142,378,361],{"class":156},[142,380,381],{"class":364},"'click'",[142,383,384],{"class":156},", () ",[142,386,387],{"class":148},"=>",[142,389,390],{"class":156}," {\n",[142,392,393,396,399,401,404],{"class":144,"line":194},[142,394,395],{"class":156},"    console.",[142,397,398],{"class":152},"log",[142,400,361],{"class":156},[142,402,403],{"class":364},"'clicked'",[142,405,368],{"class":156},[142,407,408],{"class":144,"line":209},[142,409,410],{"class":156},"  });\n",[142,412,413],{"class":144,"line":229},[142,414,232],{"class":156},[142,416,417],{"class":144,"line":235},[142,418,239],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":238},[142,420,421,424],{"class":144,"line":242},[142,422,423],{"class":152},"addLister",[142,425,248],{"class":156},[17,427,428,429,431],{},"Simple enough — ",[139,430,423],{}," finds an element and attaches a click handler. But what if you remove the element from the DOM afterwards?",[132,433,435],{"className":134,"code":434,"language":136,"meta":137,"style":137},"function addLister() {\n  const el = document.getElementById('el');\n  el.addEventListener('click', () => {\n    console.log('clicked');\n  });\n}\n\naddLister();\n\nconst el = document.getElementById('el');\nel.remove();\n",[139,436,437,445,463,479,491,495,499,503,509,514,534],{"__ignoreMap":137},[142,438,439,441,443],{"class":144,"line":145},[142,440,149],{"class":148},[142,442,341],{"class":152},[142,444,157],{"class":156},[142,446,447,449,451,453,455,457,459,461],{"class":144,"line":160},[142,448,163],{"class":148},[142,450,350],{"class":166},[142,452,170],{"class":148},[142,454,355],{"class":156},[142,456,358],{"class":152},[142,458,361],{"class":156},[142,460,365],{"class":364},[142,462,368],{"class":156},[142,464,465,467,469,471,473,475,477],{"class":144,"line":179},[142,466,373],{"class":156},[142,468,376],{"class":152},[142,470,361],{"class":156},[142,472,381],{"class":364},[142,474,384],{"class":156},[142,476,387],{"class":148},[142,478,390],{"class":156},[142,480,481,483,485,487,489],{"class":144,"line":194},[142,482,395],{"class":156},[142,484,398],{"class":152},[142,486,361],{"class":156},[142,488,403],{"class":364},[142,490,368],{"class":156},[142,492,493],{"class":144,"line":209},[142,494,410],{"class":156},[142,496,497],{"class":144,"line":229},[142,498,232],{"class":156},[142,500,501],{"class":144,"line":235},[142,502,239],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":238},[142,504,505,507],{"class":144,"line":242},[142,506,423],{"class":152},[142,508,248],{"class":156},[142,510,512],{"class":144,"line":511},9,[142,513,239],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":238},[142,515,517,520,522,524,526,528,530,532],{"class":144,"line":516},10,[142,518,519],{"class":148},"const",[142,521,350],{"class":166},[142,523,170],{"class":148},[142,525,355],{"class":156},[142,527,358],{"class":152},[142,529,361],{"class":156},[142,531,365],{"class":364},[142,533,368],{"class":156},[142,535,537,540,543],{"class":144,"line":536},11,[142,538,539],{"class":156},"el.",[142,541,542],{"class":152},"remove",[142,544,248],{"class":156},[17,546,547,548,551],{},"Now you've got a leak. Even though ",[139,549,550],{},"el"," is gone from the page, the listener is still attached, which means GC can't reclaim that DOM node's memory. Repeat this pattern enough times and memory keeps climbing.",[44,553,554],{},[17,555,556,558,559,562,563,565],{},[49,557,51],{},"\nCleanup is easy — call ",[139,560,561],{},"removeEventListener"," when you're done. This is exactly why so many devs nag you to always pair ",[139,564,376],{}," with a removal.",[323,567,569],{"id":568},"timers","Timers",[17,571,572],{},"If you've built a Pomodoro timer or anything else time-based, you know the pattern:",[132,574,576],{"className":134,"code":575,"language":136,"meta":137,"style":137},"setInterval(() => {\n  \u002F\u002F do something\n}, 1000);\n",[139,577,578,590,596],{"__ignoreMap":137},[142,579,580,583,586,588],{"class":144,"line":145},[142,581,582],{"class":152},"setInterval",[142,584,585],{"class":156},"(() ",[142,587,387],{"class":148},[142,589,390],{"class":156},[142,591,592],{"class":144,"line":160},[142,593,595],{"class":594},"sQrFR","  \u002F\u002F do something\n",[142,597,598,601,604],{"class":144,"line":179},[142,599,600],{"class":156},"}, ",[142,602,603],{"class":166},"1000",[142,605,368],{"class":156},[17,607,608,609,611,612,615],{},"Timers are another leak vector. A ",[139,610,582],{}," that you never ",[139,613,614],{},"clearInterval"," just keeps running, forever, and consuming memory every tick.",[17,617,618,619,621],{},"I once saw a system that fired a ",[139,620,582],{}," whenever some event happened — but the developer forgot to clear the previous timer first. So every event spawned a new timer alongside the old ones. It blew up spectacularly.",[323,623,625],{"id":624},"closures","Closures",[17,627,628,629,632],{},"Closures are common in JavaScript — React's ",[139,630,631],{},"useState"," uses closures under the hood — and they can leak memory too. Why? Let's get into it.",[17,634,635],{},"Closures let you encapsulate private variables and preserved state. You can write some pretty fun stuff with them, like a stored-value card example:",[132,637,639],{"className":134,"code":638,"language":136,"meta":137,"style":137},"function myMoney(storage) {\n  var money = storage;\n  console.log(money);\n  return function(price) {\n    return {\n      nowMoney: function () {\n        return console.log(money);\n      },\n      count: function (price) {\n        if(money \u003C price) return console.log('Insufficient balance. Current balance: ' + money + ' $');\n        if (!money \u003C= 0) {\n          return money = money - price;\n        }\n        return console.log('Deduction failed. Current balance: ' + money + ' $');\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nvar ming = myMoney(500);\nvar mei = myMoney(5000);\nvar wang = myMoney(30000);\n\nming().count(100);\nming().count(100);\nming().count(300);\nming().nowMoney();\nmei().count(1600);\nmei().count(100);\nmei().count(600);\nmei().nowMoney();\nwang().count(300);\nwang().nowMoney();\n",[139,640,641,657,671,681,695,702,715,727,732,748,786,806,824,830,854,860,866,872,877,882,902,921,940,945,964,979,995,1007,1024,1039,1055,1066,1082],{"__ignoreMap":137},[142,642,643,645,648,650,654],{"class":144,"line":145},[142,644,149],{"class":148},[142,646,647],{"class":152}," myMoney",[142,649,361],{"class":156},[142,651,653],{"class":652},"s_sBn","storage",[142,655,656],{"class":156},") {\n",[142,658,659,662,665,668],{"class":144,"line":160},[142,660,661],{"class":148},"  var",[142,663,664],{"class":156}," money ",[142,666,667],{"class":148},"=",[142,669,670],{"class":156}," storage;\n",[142,672,673,676,678],{"class":144,"line":179},[142,674,675],{"class":156},"  console.",[142,677,398],{"class":152},[142,679,680],{"class":156},"(money);\n",[142,682,683,685,688,690,693],{"class":144,"line":194},[142,684,212],{"class":148},[142,686,687],{"class":148}," function",[142,689,361],{"class":156},[142,691,692],{"class":652},"price",[142,694,656],{"class":156},[142,696,697,700],{"class":144,"line":209},[142,698,699],{"class":148},"    return",[142,701,390],{"class":156},[142,703,704,707,710,712],{"class":144,"line":229},[142,705,706],{"class":152},"      nowMoney",[142,708,709],{"class":156},": ",[142,711,149],{"class":148},[142,713,714],{"class":156}," () {\n",[142,716,717,720,723,725],{"class":144,"line":235},[142,718,719],{"class":148},"        return",[142,721,722],{"class":156}," console.",[142,724,398],{"clas